<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the <b>logarithm</b> of a number is the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponent" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Expo=
nent">exponent</a> by which another fixed value, the <b>base</b>, must be r=
aised to produce that number. For example, the logarithm of <span class=3D"=
texhtml">1000</span> to base <span class=3D"texhtml">10</span> is <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml">3</span>, because <span class=3D"texhtml">1000</span> is <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml">10</span> to the <span class=3D"texhtml">3</span>rd po=
wer: <span class=3D"texhtml">1000 =3D 10<sup>3</sup> =3D 10=E2=80=89=C3=97=
=E2=80=8910=E2=80=89=C3=97=E2=80=8910</span>. More generally, if <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D <i>b</i><sup><i>y</i></sup></span>, then <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span> is the logarith=
m of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> to =
base <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>, wr=
itten <span class=3D"texhtml">log<sub><i>b</i></sub> <i>x</i></span>, so <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml">log<sub>10</sub> 1000 =3D 3</span>. As a single-varia=
ble function, the logarithm to base <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">b</span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Inverse_function" title=3D"Inverse function">inverse</a> of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation" title=3D"Exponentiation">exponen=
tiation</a> with base <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">b</span>.
</p><p>The logarithm base <span class=3D"texhtml">10</span> is called the <=
i>decimal</i> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_logarithm"=
 title=3D"Common logarithm"><i>common</i> logarithm</a> and is commonly use=
d in science and engineering. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Natural_logarithm" title=3D"Natural logarithm"><i>natural</i> logarithm</a>=
 has the number&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E_(mathematic=
al_constant)" title=3D"E (mathematical constant)"><span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>e</i> =E2=89=88 2.718</span></a> as its base; its use is widespread in ma=
thematics and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Ph=
ysics">physics</a> because of its very simple <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Derivative" title=3D"Derivative">derivative</a>. The <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_logarithm" title=3D"Binary logarithm"=
><i>binary</i> logarithm</a> uses base <span class=3D"texhtml">2</span> and=
 is widely used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_scienc=
e" title=3D"Computer science">computer science</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Information_theory" title=3D"Information theory">informat=
ion theory</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Music_theory" titl=
e=3D"Music theory">music theory</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Photography" title=3D"Photography">photography</a>. When the base is=
 unambiguous from the context or irrelevant it is often omitted, and the lo=
garithm is written <span class=3D"texhtml">log=E2=80=89<i>x</i></span>.
</p><p>Logarithms were introduced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/John_Napier" title=3D"John Napier">John Napier</a> in 1614 as a means of=
 simplifying calculations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> They w=
ere rapidly adopted by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Navigator" =
title=3D"Navigator">navigators</a>, scientists, engineers, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surveying" title=3D"Surveying">surveyors</a>, and =
others to perform high-accuracy computations more easily. Using <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm_table" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Logarithm table">logarithm tables</a>, tedious multi-digit multiplicati=
on steps can be replaced by table look-ups and simpler addition. This is po=
ssible because the logarithm of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Product_(mathematics)" title=3D"Product (mathematics)">product</a> is the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Summation" title=3D"Summation">sum<=
/a> of the logarithms of the factors:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle \log _{b}(xy)=3D\log _{b}x+\log _{b}y,}">
