</p><p>provided that <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">b</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</=
span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span=
> are all positive and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> =E2=89=A0 1</span>.=
 The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slide_rule" title=3D"Slide ru=
le">slide rule</a>, also based on logarithms, allows quick calculations wit=
hout tables, but at lower precision. The present-day notion of logarithms c=
omes from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonhard_Euler" title=3D=
"Leonhard Euler">Leonhard Euler</a>, who connected them to the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_function" title=3D"Exponential fun=
ction">exponential function</a> in the 18th century, and who also introduce=
d the letter <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</s=
pan> as the base of natural logarithms.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-2"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithmic_scale" title=3D=
"Logarithmic scale">Logarithmic scales</a> reduce wide-ranging quantities t=
o smaller scopes. For example, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Decibel" title=3D"Decibel">decibel</a> (dB) is a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Units_of_measurement" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Units =
of measurement">unit</a> used to express <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Level_(logarithmic_quantity)" title=3D"Level (logarithmic quantity)"=
>ratio as logarithms</a>, mostly for signal power and amplitude (of which <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sound_pressure" title=3D"Sound pres=
sure">sound pressure</a> is a common example). In chemistry, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PH" title=3D"PH">pH</a> is a logarithmic measure=
 for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acid" title=3D"Acid">acid=
ity</a> of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aqueous_solution" ti=
tle=3D"Aqueous solution">aqueous solution</a>. Logarithms are commonplace i=
n scientific <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formula" title=3D"For=
mula">formulae</a>, and in measurements of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Computational_complexity_theory" title=3D"Computational comple=
xity theory">complexity of algorithms</a> and of geometric objects called <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractal" title=3D"Fractal">fractals=
</a>. They help to describe <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freque=
ncy" title=3D"Frequency">frequency</a> ratios of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Interval_(music)" title=3D"Interval (music)">musical interva=
ls</a>, appear in formulas counting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prime numbers</a> or <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stirling%27s_approximation" title=3D"Stirling's a=
pproximation">approximating</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fa=
ctorial" title=3D"Factorial">factorials</a>, inform some models in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychophysics" title=3D"Psychophysics">ps=
ychophysics</a>, and can aid in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fo=
rensic_accounting" title=3D"Forensic accounting">forensic accounting</a>.
</p><p>The concept of logarithm as the inverse of exponentiation extends to=
 other mathematical structures as well. However, in general settings, the l=
ogarithm tends to be a multi-valued function. For example, the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_logarithm" title=3D"Complex logarithm"=
>complex logarithm</a> is the multi-valued <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Inverse_function" title=3D"Inverse function">inverse</a> of the co=
mplex exponential function. Similarly, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Discrete_logarithm" title=3D"Discrete logarithm">discrete logarith=
m</a> is the multi-valued inverse of the exponential function in finite gro=
ups; it has uses in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public-key_cry=
ptography" title=3D"Public-key cryptography">public-key cryptography</a>.
</p>
