igure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addition" title=3D"Addition">Ad=
dition</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplication" title=
=3D"Multiplication">multiplication</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Exponentiation" title=3D"Exponentiation">exponentiation</a> are t=
hree of the most fundamental arithmetic operations. The inverse of addition=
 is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subtraction" title=3D"Subtract=
ion">subtraction</a>, and the inverse of multiplication is <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_(mathematics)" title=3D"Division (mathema=
tics)">division</a>. Similarly, a logarithm is the inverse operation of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation" title=3D"Exponentiati=
on">exponentiation</a>. Exponentiation is when a number <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>, the <i>base</i>, is raised=
 to a certain power <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">y</span>, the <i>exponent</i>, to give a value <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>; this is denoted
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle b^{y}=3Dx.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
