</p><p>Thus, <span class=3D"texhtml">log<sub>10</sub>=E2=80=89(<i>x</i>)</s=
pan> is related to the number of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D=
ecimal_digit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Decimal digit">decimal digits<=
/a> of a positive integer <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">x</span>: The number of digits is the smallest <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integer</a> strictly bigge=
r than <span class=3D"nowrap"> <span class=3D"texhtml"> log<sub>10</sub>=E2=
=80=89(<i>x</i>)</span> .</span><sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-9"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
For example, <span class=3D"texhtml">log<sub>10</sub>(5986)</span> is appro=
ximately 3.78&nbsp;. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floor_and=
_ceiling_functions" title=3D"Floor and ceiling functions">next integer abov=
e</a> it is 4, which is the number of digits of 5986. Both the natural loga=
rithm and the binary logarithm are used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Information_theory" title=3D"Information theory">information theor=
y</a>, corresponding to the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Nat_(unit)" title=3D"Nat (unit)">nats</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Bit" title=3D"Bit">bits</a> as the fundamental units of informa=
tion, respectively.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Binary logarithms are also used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Computer_science" title=3D"Computer science">computer science</a>, where t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_numeral_system" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Binary numeral system">binary system</a> is ubiquito=
us; in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Music_theory" title=3D"Musi=
c theory">music theory</a>, where a pitch ratio of two (the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octave" title=3D"Octave">octave</a>) is ubiquitou=
s and the number of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cent_(music)" =
title=3D"Cent (music)">cents</a> between any two pitches is a scaled versio=
n of the binary logarithm, or log&nbsp;2 times 1200, of the pitch ratio (th=
at is, 100&nbsp;cents per <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semitone=
" title=3D"Semitone">semitone</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/12_tone_equal_temperament" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"12 tone equal =
temperament">conventional equal temperament</a>), or equivalently the log b=
ase <span class=3D"nowrap"> <span class=3D"texhtml">2<sup>1/1200</sup> </sp=
an>&nbsp;;</span> and in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Photograp=
hy" title=3D"Photography">photography</a> rescaled base&nbsp;2 logarithms a=
re used to measure <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exposure_value"=
 title=3D"Exposure value">exposure values</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Luminance" title=3D"Luminance">light levels</a>, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exposure_time" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"E=
xposure time">exposure times</a>, lens <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Aperture" title=3D"Aperture">apertures</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Film_speed" title=3D"Film speed">film speeds</a> in "sto=
ps".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The abbreviation <span class=3D"texhtml">log=E2=80=89<i>x</i></span>=
 is often used when the intended base can be inferred based on the context =
or discipline, or when the base is indeterminate or immaterial. Common loga=
rithms (base 10), historically used in logarithm tables and slide rules, ar=
e a basic tool for measurement and computation in many areas of science and=
 engineering; in these contexts <span class=3D"texhtml">log=E2=80=89<i>x</i=
></span> still often means the base ten logarithm.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_=
note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> In mathematics <span class=3D"texhtml">log=E2=80=89<i>=
x</i></span> usually refers to the natural logarithm (base <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cit=
e_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
In computer science and information theory, <span class=3D"texhtml">log</sp=
an> often refers to binary logarithms (base 2).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_not=
e-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> The following table lists common notations for logarithms=
 to these bases. The "ISO notation" column lists designations suggested by =
