<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_logarithm=
s" title=3D"History of logarithms">History of logarithms</a></div>
<p>The history of logarithms in seventeenth-century Europe saw the discover=
y of a new <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)"=
 title=3D"Function (mathematics)">function</a> that extended the realm of a=
nalysis beyond the scope of algebraic methods. The method of logarithms was=
 publicly propounded by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Napie=
r" title=3D"John Napier">John Napier</a> in 1614, in a book titled <i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirifici_Logarithmorum_Canonis_Descript=
io" title=3D"Mirifici Logarithmorum Canonis Descriptio">Mirifici Logarithmo=
rum Canonis Descriptio</a></i> (<i>Description of the Wonderful Canon of Lo=
garithms</i>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logari=
thm#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Prior to Napier's invention, there had been o=
ther techniques of similar scopes, such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Prosthaphaeresis" title=3D"Prosthaphaeresis">prosthaphaeresis<=
/a> or the use of tables of progressions, extensively developed by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jost_B%C3%BCrgi" title=3D"Jost B=C3=BCrgi=
">Jost B=C3=BCrgi</a> around 1600.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-folkerts_24-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note=
-folkerts-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Napi=
er coined the term for logarithm in Middle Latin, <span title=3D"Latin-lang=
uage text"><i lang=3D"la">logarithmus</i></span>, literally meaning <span c=
lass=3D"gloss-quot">'</span><span class=3D"gloss-text">ratio-number</span><=
span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span>, derived from the Greek <span title=3D"A=
ncient Greek (to 1453)-language romanization"><i lang=3D"grc-Latn">logos</i=
></span> <span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span><span class=3D"gloss-text">prop=
ortion, ratio, word</span><span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span> + <span title=
=3D"Ancient Greek (to 1453)-language romanization"><i lang=3D"grc-Latn">ari=
thmos</i></span> <span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span><span class=3D"gloss-te=
xt">number</span><span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span>.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_logarithm" title=
=3D"Common logarithm">common logarithm</a> of a number is the index of that=
 power of ten which equals the number.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-26"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> Speaking of a number as requiring so many figures is a rough allus=
ion to common logarithm, and was referred to by <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Archimedes" title=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> as the "order=
 of a number".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The first real =
logarithms were heuristic methods to turn multiplication into addition, thu=
s facilitating rapid computation. Some of these methods used tables derived=
 from trigonometric identities.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-28"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Such methods are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prosthap=
haeresis" title=3D"Prosthaphaeresis">prosthaphaeresis</a>.
</p><p>Invention of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(=
mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">function</a> now known as th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_logarithm" title=3D"Natu=
ral logarithm">natural logarithm</a> began as an attempt to perform a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrature_(mathematics)" title=3D"Quad=
rature (mathematics)">quadrature</a> of a rectangular <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbola" title=3D"Hyperbola">hyperbola</a> by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%A9goire_de_Saint-Vincent" title=3D"=
Gr=C3=A9goire de Saint-Vincent">Gr=C3=A9goire de Saint-Vincent</a>, a Belgi=
an Jesuit residing in Prague. Archimedes had written <i><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Quadrature_of_the_Parabola" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"The Quadrature of the Parabola">The Quadrature of the Parabola</a=
></i> in the third century BC, but a quadrature for the hyperbola eluded al=
l efforts until Saint-Vincent published his results in 1647. The relation t=
hat the logarithm provides between a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Geometric_progression" title=3D"Geometric progression">geometric progres=
sion</a> in its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argument_of_a_func=
tion" title=3D"Argument of a function">argument</a> and an <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic_progression" title=3D"Arithmetic progre=
ssion">arithmetic progression</a> of values, prompted <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/A._A._de_Sarasa" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"A. A. d=
e Sarasa">A. A. de Sarasa</a> to make the connection of Saint-Vincent's qua=
drature and the tradition of logarithms in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Prosthaphaeresis" title=3D"Prosthaphaeresis">prosthaphaeresis</a>,=
 leading to the term "hyperbolic logarithm", a synonym for natural logarith=
m. Soon the new function was appreciated by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Christiaan_Huygens" title=3D"Christiaan Huygens">Christiaan Huyge=
ns</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Gregory_(mathema=
tician)" title=3D"James Gregory (mathematician)">James Gregory</a>. The not=
ation <span class=3D"texhtml">Log <i>y</i></span> was adopted by <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz" title=3D"Gottfrie=
d Wilhelm Leibniz">Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz</a> in 1675,<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarith=
m#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the next year he connected it to the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Integral calculus">integral</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-element m=
we-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-math=
ml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Mat=
h/MathML" alttext=3D"{\textstyle \int {\frac {dy}{y}}.}">
