<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Logarithm_tables,_slide_rul=
es,_and_historical_applications"><span id=3D"Logarithm_tables.2C_slide_rule=
s.2C_and_historical_applications"></span>Logarithm tables, slide rules, and=
 historical applications<span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Antilogarithm"></span>=
</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Logarithm tables, =
slide rules, and historical applications"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Logarithms_Britannica_1797.png" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/thumb/8/82/Logarithms_Britannica_1797.png/250px-Logarithms_Britannica_1797=
.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"89" class=3D"mw-file-eleme=
nt" data-file-width=3D"997" data-file-height=3D"354"></a><figcaption>The 17=
97 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica=
" title=3D"Encyclop=C3=A6dia Britannica">Encyclop=C3=A6dia Britannica</a></=
i> explanation of logarithms</figcaption></figure>
<p>By simplifying difficult calculations before calculators and computers b=
ecame available, logarithms contributed to the advance of science, especial=
ly <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomy" title=3D"Astronomy">=
astronomy</a>. They were critical to advances in <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Surveying" title=3D"Surveying">surveying</a>, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celestial_navigation" title=3D"Celestial navigat=
ion">celestial navigation</a>, and other domains. <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Pierre-Simon_Laplace" title=3D"Pierre-Simon Laplace">Pierre=
-Simon Laplace</a> called logarithms
</p>
<blockquote><p>... [a]n admirable artifice which, by reducing to a few days=
 the labour of many months, doubles the life of the astronomer, and spares =
him the errors and disgust inseparable from long calculations.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Log=
arithm#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>As the function <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span><sup><i>x</i></sup=
></span> is the inverse function of <span class=3D"texhtml">log<sub><i>b</i=
></sub>=E2=80=89<i>x</i></span>, it has been called an <b>antilogarithm</b>=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Nowadays, this function is m=
ore commonly called an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential=
_function" title=3D"Exponential function">exponential function</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Log_tables">Log tables</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Log tables"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A key tool that enabled the practical use of logarithms was the <i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Log_table" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Log table">table of logarithms</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-33=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> The first such table was compiled by <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Briggs_(mathematician)" title=3D"Henry Briggs (mathe=
matician)">Henry Briggs</a> in 1617, immediately after Napier's invention b=
ut with the innovation of using 10 as the base. Briggs' first table contain=
ed the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_logarithm" title=3D"=
Common logarithm">common logarithms</a> of all integers in the range from 1=
 to 1000, with a precision of 14&nbsp;digits. Subsequently, tables with inc=
reasing scope were written. These tables listed the values of <span class=
=3D"texhtml">log<sub>10</sub>=E2=80=89<i>x</i></span>  for any number&nbsp;=
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> in a cer=
tain range, at a certain precision. Base-10 logarithms were universally use=
d for computation, hence the name common logarithm, since numbers that diff=
er by factors of 10 have logarithms that differ by integers. The common log=
arithm of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span=
> can be separated into an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer=
_part" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Integer part">integer part</a> and a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractional_part" title=3D"Fraction=
al part">fractional part</a>, known as the characteristic and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mantissa_(logarithm)" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Mantissa (logarithm)">mantissa</a>. Tables of logarithms need only in=
clude the mantissa, as the characteristic can be easily determined by count=
ing digits from the decimal point.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-34"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> The characteristic of <span class=3D"texhtml">10 =C2=B7 <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span></span> is one plus the=
 characteristic of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">x</span>, and their mantissas are the same. Thus using a three-digit log =
table, the logarithm of 3542 is approximated by
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle {\begin{aligned}\log _{10}3542&amp;=3D\log _{10}(1000\c=
dot 3.542)\\&amp;=3D3+\log _{10}3.542\\&amp;\approx 3+\log _{10}3.54\end{al=
igned}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
