<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Slide_rules">Slide rules</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Slide rules"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slide_rule" title=3D=
"Slide rule">Slide rule</a></div>
<p>Another critical application was the slide rule, a pair of logarithmical=
ly divided scales used for calculation. The non-sliding logarithmic scale, =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunter%27s_rule" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Gunter's rule">Gunter's rule</a>, was invented shortly after =
Napier's invention. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Oughtr=
ed" title=3D"William Oughtred">William Oughtred</a> enhanced it to create t=
he slide rule=E2=80=94a pair of logarithmic scales movable with respect to =
each other. Numbers are placed on sliding scales at distances proportional =
to the differences between their logarithms. Sliding the upper scale approp=
riately amounts to mechanically adding logarithms, as illustrated here:
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-center" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Slide_rule_example2_with_lab=
els.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"A slide rule: two rectan=
gles with logarithmically ticked axes, arrangement to add the distance from=
 1 to 2 to the distance from 1 to 3, indicating the product 6." src=3D"http=
s://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/Slide_rule_example2_w=
ith_labels.svg/250px-Slide_rule_example2_with_labels.svg.png" decoding=3D"a=
sync" width=3D"250" height=3D"58" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"119"></a><figcaption>Schematic depiction of a =
slide rule. Starting from 2 on the lower scale, add the distance to 3 on th=
e upper scale to reach the product&nbsp;6. The slide rule works because it =
is marked such that the distance from 1 to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> is proportional to the logarithm of <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>.</figcaption=
></figure>
<p>For example, adding the distance from 1 to 2 on the lower scale to the d=
istance from 1 to 3 on the upper scale yields a product of 6, which is read=
 off at the lower part. The slide rule was an essential calculating tool fo=
r engineers and scientists until the 1970s, because it allows, at the expen=
se of precision, much faster computation than techniques based on tables.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-ReferenceA_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-ReferenceA-35"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Analytic_properties">Analyt=
ic properties</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DLogarithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Ana=
lytic properties"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<p>A deeper study of logarithms requires the concept of a <i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathe=
matics)">function</a></i>. A function is a rule that, given one number, pro=
duces another number.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An examp=
le is the function producing the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">x</span>-th power of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">b</span> from any real number&nbsp;<span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>, where the base&nbsp;<span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> is a fixed numb=
er. This function is written as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) =
=3D <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span><sup>=
=E2=80=89<i>x</i></sup></span>. When <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">b</span> is positive and unequal to 1, we show below th=
at <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span> is in=
vertible when considered as a function from the reals to the positive reals=
.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Existence">Existence</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Existence"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Let <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> b=
e a positive real number not equal to 1 and let <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
f</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">b</span><sup>=E2=80=89<i>x</i></sup></span>.
</p><p>It is a standard result in real analysis that any continuous strictl=
y monotonic function is bijective between its domain and range. This fact f=
ollows from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intermediate_value=
_theorem" title=3D"Intermediate value theorem">intermediate value theorem</=
a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-LangIII.3_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-LangIII.3-37"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Now,=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span> is <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monotonic_function" title=3D"Monotonic=
 function">strictly increasing</a> (for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> &g=
t; 1</span>), or strictly decreasing (for <span class=3D"texhtml">0 &lt; <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> &lt; 1</sp=
an>),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-LangIV.2_38-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-LangIV.2-38"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is c=
ontinuous, has domain <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inli=
ne"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"di=
splay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D=
