-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.838ex; width:20.82ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle f(=
xy)=3Df(x)+f(y).}"></span>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Graph_of_the_logarithm_func=
tion">Graph of the logarithm function</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Graph of the logarithm function"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Logarithm_inversefunctiontoex=
p.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"The graphs of two function=
s." src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Logari=
thm_inversefunctiontoexp.svg/250px-Logarithm_inversefunctiontoexp.svg.png" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"291" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"240" data-file-height=3D"279"></a><figcaption>The graph o=
f the logarithm function <span class=3D"texhtml">log<sub><i>b</i></sub>=E2=
=80=89(<i>x</i>)</span> (blue) is obtained by <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Reflection_(mathematics)" title=3D"Reflection (mathematics)">re=
flecting</a> the graph of the function <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i><sup=
><i>x</i></sup></span> (red) at the diagonal line (<span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>x</i> =3D <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">y</s=
pan></span>).</figcaption></figure>
<p>As discussed above, the function <span class=3D"texhtml">log<sub><i>b</i=
></sub></span> is the inverse to the exponential function <span class=3D"mw=
e-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inli=
ne mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www=
.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle x\mapsto b^{x}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=A6<!-- =E2=86=A6 --></mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>b</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>x</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle x\mapsto b^{x=
}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/873987f9618fe2c30ce4e72cbd1a967ff759c1d4" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:7.114ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle x\m=
apsto b^{x}}"></span>. Therefore, their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Graph_of_a_function" title=3D"Graph of a function">graphs</a> corresp=
ond to each other upon exchanging the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">x</span>- and the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span>-coordinates (or upon reflection at the dia=
gonal line <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D <i>y</i></span>), as shown =
at the right: a point <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>t</i>, <i>u</i> =3D <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span><sup><i>t</i><=
/sup>)</span> on the graph of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">f</span> yields a point <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>u</i>, <i>=
t</i> =3D log<sub><i>b</i></sub>=E2=80=89<i>u</i>)</span> on the graph of t=
he logarithm and vice versa. As a consequence, <span class=3D"texhtml">log<=
sub><i>b</i></sub>=E2=80=89(<i>x</i>)</span> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Divergent_sequence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Divergent seq=
uence">diverges to infinity</a> (gets bigger than any given number) if <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> grows to inf=
inity, provided that <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">b</span> is greater than one. In that case, <span class=3D"texhtml">log=
<sub><i>b</i></sub>(<i>x</i>)</span>  is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Increasing_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Increasing fu=
nction">increasing function</a>. For <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> &lt; =
1</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">log<sub><i>b</i></sub>=E2=80=89(<i>x</i>)=
</span> tends to minus infinity instead. When <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> approaches zero, <span class=3D"texht=
ml">log<sub><i>b</i></sub>=E2=80=89<i>x</i></span> goes to minus infinity f=
or <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> &gt; 1</span> (plus infinity for <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> &lt; 1</span>, respectively).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Derivative_and_antiderivati=
ve">Derivative and antiderivative</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=
=3D"Edit section: Derivative and antiderivative"><span>edit</span></a><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Logarithm_derivative.svg" class=3D"mw-file-de=
scription"><img alt=3D"A graph of the logarithm function and a line touchin=
g it in one point." src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/t=
humb/5/57/Logarithm_derivative.svg/250px-Logarithm_derivative.svg.png" deco=
ding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"162" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-=
file-width=3D"375" data-file-height=3D"243"></a><figcaption>The graph of th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_logarithm" title=3D"Natu=
ral logarithm">natural logarithm</a> (green) and its tangent at <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D 1.5</span> (black)</figcaption></figure>
<p>Analytic properties of functions pass to their inverses.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-LangIII.3_37-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-LangIII.3-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Thus, as <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">b</span><sup><i>x</i></sup></span> is a continuous and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differentiable_function" title=3D"Diff=
erentiable function">differentiable function</a>, so is <span class=3D"texh=
tml">log<sub><i>b</i></sub>=E2=80=89<i>y</i></span>. Roughly, a continuous =
function is differentiable if its graph has no sharp "corners". Moreover, a=
s the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative" title=3D"Derivat=
ive">derivative</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> ev=
aluates to <span class=3D"texhtml">ln(<i>b</i>) <i>b</i><sup><i>x</i></sup>=
</span> by the properties of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
xponential_function" title=3D"Exponential function">exponential function</a=
>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_rule" title=3D"Chain =
rule">chain rule</a> implies that the derivative of <span class=3D"texhtml"=
>log<sub><i>b</i></sub>=E2=80=89<i>x</i></span> is given by<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-LangIV.2_38-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-LangIV.2-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_n=
ote-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle {\frac {d}{dx}}\log _{b}x=3D{\frac {1}{x\ln b}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>d</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mi>d</mi>
              <mi>x</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <msub>
          <mi>log</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>b</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mn>1</mn>
            <mrow>
              <mi>x</mi>
              <mi>ln</mi>
              <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
              <mi>b</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\frac {d}{dx=
}}\log _{b}x=3D{\frac {1}{x\ln b}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c36ba5e891172556f0477a117831310bcd38869c" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.005ex; width:19.017ex; height:5.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {=
\frac {d}{dx}}\log _{b}x=3D{\frac {1}{x\ln b}}.}"></span>
</p><p>That is, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slope" title=
=3D"Slope">slope</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangen=
t" title=3D"Tangent">tangent</a> touching the graph of the <span class=3D"t=
exhtml">base-<i>b</i></span> logarithm at the point <span class=3D"texhtml"=
>(<i>x</i>, log<sub><i>b</i></sub>=E2=80=89(<i>x</i>))</span> equals <span =
class=3D"texhtml">1/(<i>x</i>=E2=80=89ln(<i>b</i>))</span>.
</p><p>The derivative of <span class=3D"texhtml">ln(<i>x</i>)</span> is <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml">1/<i>x</i></span>; this implies that <span class=3D"te=
xhtml">ln(<i>x</i>)</span> is the unique <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Antiderivative" title=3D"Antiderivative">antiderivative</a> of <span=
 class=3D"texhtml">1/<i>x</i></span> that has the value 0 for <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D 1</span>. It is this very simple formula that mot=
ivated to qualify as "natural" the natural logarithm; this is also one of t=
he main reasons of the importance of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/E_(mathematical_constant)" title=3D"E (mathematical constant)">const=
ant&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span>=
</a>.
</p><p>The derivative with a generalized functional argument <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> is
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle {\frac {d}{dx}}\ln f(x)=3D{\frac {f'(x)}{f(x)}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>d</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mi>d</mi>
              <mi>x</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mi>ln</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <msup>
                <mi>f</mi>
                <mo>=E2=80=B2</mo>
              </msup>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
              <mi>x</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi>f</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
              <mi>x</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\frac {d}{dx=
}}\ln f(x)=3D{\frac {f'(x)}{f(x)}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c06fb9da0538b2a1eefa892ebbfbc3fffdc98bc0" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.671ex; width:20.238ex; height:6.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {=
\frac {d}{dx}}\ln f(x)=3D{\frac {f'(x)}{f(x)}}.}"></span>
</p><p>The quotient at the right hand side is called the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithmic_derivative" title=3D"Logarithmic derivat=
ive">logarithmic derivative</a> of <i><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">f</span></i>. Computing <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f'<=
/i>(<i>x</i>)</span> by means of the derivative of <span class=3D"texhtml">=
ln(<i>f</i>(<i>x</i>))</span> is known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Logarithmic_differentiation" title=3D"Logarithmic differentiation">=
logarithmic differentiation</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-41"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
