l-align: -2.338ex; width:15.687ex; height:6.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
ln t=3D\int _{1}^{t}{\frac {1}{x}}\,dx.}"></span>
</p><p>This definition has the advantage that it does not rely on the expon=
ential function or any trigonometric functions; the definition is in terms =
of an integral of a simple reciprocal. As an integral, <span class=3D"texht=
ml">ln(<i>t</i>)</span> equals the area between the <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>-axis and the graph of the funct=
ion <span class=3D"texhtml">1/<i>x</i></span>, ranging from <span class=3D"=
texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D 1</span> to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D <i>t=
</i></span>. This is a consequence of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_calculus" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of ca=
lculus">fundamental theorem of calculus</a> and the fact that the derivativ=
e of <span class=3D"texhtml">ln(<i>x</i>)</span> is <span class=3D"texhtml"=
>1/<i>x</i></span>. Product and power logarithm formulas can be derived fro=
m this definition.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example=
, the product formula <span class=3D"texhtml">ln(<i>tu</i>) =3D ln(<i>t</i>=
) + ln(<i>u</i>)</span> is deduced as:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle {\begin{aligned}\ln(tu)&amp;=3D\int _{1}^{tu}{\frac {1}=
{x}}\,dx\\&amp;{\stackrel {(1)}{=3D}}\int _{1}^{t}{\frac {1}{x}}\,dx+\int _=
{t}^{tu}{\frac {1}{x}}\,dx\\&amp;{\stackrel {(2)}{=3D}}\ln(t)+\int _{1}^{u}=
{\frac {1}{w}}\,dw\\&amp;=3D\ln(t)+\ln(u).\end{aligned}}}">
