kipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic%E2%80%93geometric_mean" title=3D"Arithmetic=E2=
=80=93geometric mean">arithmetic=E2=80=93geometric mean</a>, or be retrieve=
d from a precalculated <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm_t=
able" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Logarithm table">logarithm table</a> t=
hat provides a fixed precision.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-48"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Newton%27s_method" title=3D"Newton's method">Newton's method</=
a>, an iterative method to solve equations approximately, can also be used =
to calculate the logarithm, because its inverse function, the exponential f=
unction, can be computed efficiently.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-50"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> Using look-up tables, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CORD=
IC" title=3D"CORDIC">CORDIC</a>-like methods can be used to compute logarit=
hms by using only the operations of addition and <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic_shift" title=3D"Arithmetic shift">bit shifts</a>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note=
-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> Moreover, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bin=
ary_logarithm#Algorithm" title=3D"Binary logarithm">binary logarithm algori=
thm</a> calculates <span class=3D"texhtml">lb(<i>x</i>)</span> <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recursion" title=3D"Recursion">recursively</a>=
, based on repeated squarings of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">x</span>, taking advantage of the relation
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
