mation"></span>Arithmetic=E2=80=93geometric mean approximation</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Arithmetic=E2=80=93geometric m=
ean approximation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic%E2%80%93geometri=
c_mean" title=3D"Arithmetic=E2=80=93geometric mean">arithmetic=E2=80=93geom=
etric mean</a> yields high-precision approximations of the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_logarithm" title=3D"Natural logarithm">nat=
ural logarithm</a>. Sasaki and Kanada showed in 1982 that it was particular=
ly fast for precisions between 400 and 1000 decimal places, while Taylor se=
ries methods were typically faster when less precision was needed. In their=
 work <span class=3D"texhtml">ln(<i>x</i>)</span> is approximated to a prec=
ision of <span class=3D"texhtml">2<sup>=E2=88=92<i>p</i></sup></span> (or <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>&nbsp;prec=
ise bits) by the following formula (due to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Friedrich Gauss">Carl Friedric=
h Gauss</a>):<sup id=3D"cite_ref-56" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-57" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarit=
hm#cite_note-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle \ln(x)\approx {\frac {\pi }{2\,\mathrm {M} \!\left(1,2^=
{2-m}/x\right)}}-m\ln(2).}">
