        <msup>
          <mn>2</mn>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>m</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>&gt;</mo>
        <msup>
          <mn>2</mn>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>p</mi>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mo>/</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>.</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle x\,2^{m}&gt;2=
^{p/2}.\,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/80443424cc40c061dba53d32f86d2d8169aa1983" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.338ex; width:12.552ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle x=
\,2^{m}&gt;2^{p/2}.\,}"></span>
</p><p>to ensure the required precision. A larger <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> makes the <span class=3D"texhtml"=
>M(<i>x</i>, <i>y</i>)</span> calculation take more steps (the initial <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> and <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span> are farther apar=
t so it takes more steps to converge) but gives more precision. The constan=
ts <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">=CF=80</span></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">ln(2)</span> can=
 be calculated with quickly converging series.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Feynman's_algorithm"><span =
id=3D"Feynman.27s_algorithm"></span>Feynman's algorithm</h3><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Feynman's algorithm"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>While at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Los_Alamos_National_La=
boratory" title=3D"Los Alamos National Laboratory">Los Alamos National Labo=
ratory</a> working on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manhatta=
n_Project" title=3D"Manhattan Project">Manhattan Project</a>, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Feynman" title=3D"Richard Feynman">Rich=
ard Feynman</a> developed a bit-processing algorithm to compute the logarit=
hm that is similar to long division and was later used in the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connection_Machine" title=3D"Connection Machine=
">Connection Machine</a>. The algorithm relies on the fact that every real =
number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> w=
here <span class=3D"texhtml">1 &lt; <i>x</i> &lt; 2</span> can be represent=
ed as a product of distinct factors of the form <span class=3D"texhtml">1 +=
 2<sup>=E2=88=92<i>k</i></sup></span>. The algorithm sequentially builds th=
at product&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P=
</span>, starting with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i> =3D 1</span> and <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> =3D 1</span>: if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
P</i> =C2=B7 (1 + 2<sup>=E2=88=92<i>k</i></sup>) &lt; <i>x</i></span>, then=
 it changes <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P</sp=
an> to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i> =C2=B7 (1 + 2<sup>=E2=88=92<i>k</i>=
</sup>)</span>. It then increases <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-=
element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y"=
 style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML=
" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle k}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>k</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle k}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c3c9a2c7b599b37105512c5d570edc034056dd40" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.211ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle k}"=
></span> by one regardless. The algorithm stops when <span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> is large enough to give the de=
sired accuracy. Because <span class=3D"texhtml">log(<i>x</i>)</span> is the=
 sum of the terms of the form <span class=3D"texhtml">log(1 + 2<sup>=E2=88=
=92<i>k</i></sup>)</span> corresponding to those <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> for which the factor <span class=
=3D"texhtml">1 + 2<sup>=E2=88=92<i>k</i></sup></span> was included in the p=
roduct&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P</sp=
an>, <span class=3D"texhtml">log(<i>x</i>)</span> may be computed by simple=
 addition, using a table of <span class=3D"texhtml">log(1 + 2<sup>=E2=88=92=
<i>k</i></sup>)</span> for all <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">k</span>. Any base may be used for the logarithm table.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Logarithm#cite_note-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Applications"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:NautilusCutawayLogarithmicSpiral.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"A photograph of a nautilus' shell." sr=
c=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/NautilusCuta=
wayLogarithmicSpiral.jpg/250px-NautilusCutawayLogarithmicSpiral.jpg" decodi=
ng=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"189" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fi=
le-width=3D"2240" data-file-height=3D"1693"></a><figcaption>A <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nautilus" title=3D"Nautilus">nautilus</a> shell=
 displaying a logarithmic spiral</figcaption></figure>
<p>Logarithms have many applications inside and outside mathematics. Some o=
f these occurrences are related to the notion of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Scale_invariance" title=3D"Scale invariance">scale invarianc=
e</a>. For example, each chamber of the shell of a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Nautilus" title=3D"Nautilus">nautilus</a> is an approximat=
e copy of the next one, scaled by a constant factor. This gives rise to a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithmic_spiral" title=3D"Logari=
thmic spiral">logarithmic spiral</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-59" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-59"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benford%27s_law" title=3D"=
Benford's law">Benford's law</a> on the distribution of leading digits can =
also be explained by scale invariance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-60" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-60"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> Logarithms are also linked to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Self-similarity" title=3D"Self-similarity">self-similarity</a>. For ex=
ample, logarithms appear in the analysis of algorithms that solve a problem=
 by dividing it into two similar smaller problems and patching their soluti=
ons.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The dimensions of self-si=
milar geometric shapes, that is, shapes whose parts resemble the overall pi=
cture are also based on logarithms. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Logarithmic_scale" title=3D"Logarithmic scale">Logarithmic scales</a> are=
 useful for quantifying the relative change of a value as opposed to its ab=
solute difference. Moreover, because the logarithmic function <span class=
=3D"texhtml">log(<i>x</i>)</span> grows very slowly for large <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>, logarithmic scales=
 are used to compress large-scale scientific data. Logarithms also occur in=
 numerous scientific formulas, such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Tsiolkovsky_rocket_equation" title=3D"Tsiolkovsky rocket equation"=
>Tsiolkovsky rocket equation</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Fenske_equation" title=3D"Fenske equation">Fenske equation</a>, or the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nernst_equation" title=3D"Nernst e=
quation">Nernst equation</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Logarithmic_scale">Logarith=
mic scale</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLo=
garithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: Logarith=
mic scale"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithmic_scale" t=
itle=3D"Logarithmic scale">Logarithmic scale</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Germany_Hyperinflation.svg" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"A graph of the value of one mark o=
ver time. The line showing its value is increasing very quickly, even with =
logarithmic scale." src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/t=
humb/4/4f/Germany_Hyperinflation.svg/250px-Germany_Hyperinflation.svg.png" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"292" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"509" data-file-height=3D"594"></a><figcaption>A logarithm=
ic chart depicting the value of one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/German_gold_mark" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"German gold mark">Goldma=
rk</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/German_Papiermark" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"German Papiermark">Papiermarks</a> during the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inflation_in_the_Weimar_Republic" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Inflation in the Weimar Republic">German hyperi=
nflation in the 1920s</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>Scientific quantities are often expressed as logarithms of other quantit=
ies, using a <i>logarithmic scale</i>. For example, the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decibel" title=3D"Decibel">decibel</a> is a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_of_measurement" title=3D"Unit of mea=
surement">unit of measurement</a> associated with <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Logarithmic-scale" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Logarithm=
ic-scale">logarithmic-scale</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le=
vel_quantity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Level quantity">quantities</a>=
. It is based on the common logarithm of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Ratio" title=3D"Ratio">ratios</a>=E2=80=9410&nbsp;times the common l=
ogarithm of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_(physics)" tit=
le=3D"Power (physics)">power</a> ratio or 20&nbsp;times the common logarith=
m of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voltage" title=3D"Voltage">=
voltage</a> ratio. It is used to quantify the attenuation or amplification =
of electrical signals,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-62"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> to de=
scribe power levels of sounds in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
coustics" title=3D"Acoustics">acoustics</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note=
-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absorbanc=
e" title=3D"Absorbance">absorbance</a> of light in the fields of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectrometer" title=3D"Spectrometer">spectro=
metry</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optics" title=3D"Opt=
ics">optics</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal-to-noi=
se_ratio" title=3D"Signal-to-noise ratio">signal-to-noise ratio</a> describ=
ing the amount of unwanted <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noise_(=
electronic)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Noise (electronic)">noise</a> i=
n relation to a (meaningful) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signa=
l_(information_theory)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Signal (information =
theory)">signal</a> is also measured in decibels.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-64" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_n=
ote-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> In a similar vein, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Peak_signal-to-noise_ratio" title=3D"Peak signal-to-noise ratio">p=
eak signal-to-noise ratio</a> is commonly used to assess the quality of sou=
nd and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_compression" title=3D=
"Image compression">image compression</a> methods using the logarithm.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-65" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The strength of an earthquake is measured by taking the common logar=
ithm of the energy emitted at the quake. This is used in the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moment_magnitude_scale" title=3D"Moment magnitud=
e scale">moment magnitude scale</a> or the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Richter_magnitude_scale" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Richter ma=
gnitude scale">Richter magnitude scale</a>. For example, a 5.0 earthquake r=
eleases 32&nbsp;times <span class=3D"texhtml">(10<sup>1.5</sup>)</span> and=
 a 6.0 releases 1000&nbsp;times <span class=3D"texhtml">(10<sup>3</sup>)</s=
pan> the energy of a 4.0.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-66"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apparent_magnitude" title=3D"Apparent =
magnitude">Apparent magnitude</a> measures the brightness of stars logarith=
mically.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemistry" title=3D"Chemistry">chemistry</a> the neg=
ative of the decimal logarithm, the decimal <b><span class=3D"vanchor"><spa=
n id=3D"cologarithm"></span><span class=3D"vanchor-text">cologarithm</span>=
</span></b>, is indicated by the letter p.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Jens_68-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_n=
ote-Jens-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> For instance, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/PH" title=3D"PH">pH</a> is the decimal cologarithm of the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Activity_(chemistry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Activity (chemistry)">activity</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Hydronium" title=3D"Hydronium">hydronium</a> ions (the form <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrogen" title=3D"Hydrogen">hydrogen<=
/a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion" title=3D"Ion">ions</a> <s=
pan class=3D"Unicode">=E2=80=8A</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Hydron" title=3D"Hydron">H<sup>+</sup></a> take in water).<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-69" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Log=
arithm#cite_note-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The activity of hydronium ions in neutral =
water is 10<sup>=E2=88=927</sup>&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Molar_concentration" title=3D"Molar concentration">mol=C2=B7L<sup>=E2=
=88=921</sup></a>, hence a pH of 7. Vinegar typically has a pH of about 3. =
The difference of 4 corresponds to a ratio of 10<sup>4</sup> of the activit=
y, that is, vinegar's hydronium ion activity is about <span class=3D"texhtm=
l">10<sup>=E2=88=923</sup> mol=C2=B7L<sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semi-log_plot" title=3D"Sem=
i-log plot">Semilog</a> (log=E2=80=93linear) graphs use the logarithmic sca=
le concept for visualization: one axis, typically the vertical one, is scal=
ed logarithmically. For example, the chart at the right compresses the stee=
p increase from 1&nbsp;million to 1&nbsp;trillion to the same space (on the=
 vertical axis) as the increase from 1 to 1&nbsp;million. In such graphs, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_function" title=3D"Expo=
nential function">exponential functions</a> of the form <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D <i>a</i> =C2=B7 <i>b</i><span style=3D"padding-=
left:0.12em;"><sup><i>x</i></sup></span></span> appear as straight lines wi=
th <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slope" title=3D"Slope">slope</a=
> equal to the logarithm of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">b</span>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Log-log_plot"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Log-log plot">Log-log</a> graphs scale both=
 axes logarithmically, which causes functions of the form <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>) =3D <i>a</i> =C2=B7 <i>x</i><span style=3D"paddin=
g-left:0.12em;"><sup><i>k</i></sup></span></span> to be depicted as straigh=
t lines with slope equal to the exponent&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span>. This is applied in visualizing and a=
nalyzing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_law" title=3D"Power=
 law">power laws</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-70" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Psychology">Psychology</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Psychology"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Logarithms occur in several laws describing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Human_perception" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Human percept=
ion">human perception</a>:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-71" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-71"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-72" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-72"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Hick%27s_law" title=3D"Hick's law">Hick's law</a> proposes a logari=
thmic relation between the time individuals take to choose an alternative a=
nd the number of choices they have.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-73" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-73"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fitts%27s_law" title=3D"Fitt=
s's law">Fitts's law</a> predicts that the time required to rapidly move to=
 a target area is a logarithmic function of the ratio between the distance =
to a target and the size of the target.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-74" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-74"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychophysics" title=
=3D"Psychophysics">psychophysics</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Weber%E2%80%93Fechner_law" title=3D"Weber=E2=80=93Fechner law">Webe=
r=E2=80=93Fechner law</a> proposes a logarithmic relationship between <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stimulus_(psychology)" title=3D"Stimulu=
s (psychology)">stimulus</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
ensation_(psychology)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sensation (psychology=
)">sensation</a> such as the actual vs. the perceived weight of an item a p=
erson is carrying.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-75" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-75"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>70<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (This "law"=
, however, is less realistic than more recent models, such as <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stevens%27s_power_law" title=3D"Stevens's power=
 law">Stevens's power law</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-76" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-76"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>71<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
)
</p><p>Psychological studies found that individuals with little mathematics=
 education tend to estimate quantities logarithmically, that is, they posit=
ion a number on an unmarked line according to its logarithm, so that 10 is =
positioned as close to 100 as 100 is to 1000. Increasing education shifts t=
his to a linear estimate (positioning 1000 10 times as far away) in some ci=
rcumstances, while logarithms are used when the numbers to be plotted are d=
ifficult to plot linearly.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-77" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-77"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-78" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-78"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>73<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Probability_theory_and_stat=
istics">Probability theory and statistics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29"=
 title=3D"Edit section: Probability theory and statistics"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:PDF-log_normal_distributions.=
svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"Three asymmetric PDF curves"=
 src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/PDF-log_n=
ormal_distributions.svg/250px-PDF-log_normal_distributions.svg.png" decodin=
g=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fil=
e-width=3D"390" data-file-height=3D"390"></a><figcaption>Three <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_density_function" title=3D"Probabi=
lity density function">probability density functions</a> (PDF) of random va=
riables with log-normal distributions. The location parameter&nbsp;<span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml">=CE=BC</span>, which is zero for all three of the PDFs show=
n, is the mean of the logarithm of the random variable, not the mean of the=
 variable itself.</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Benfords_law_illustrated_by_w=
orld%27s_countries_population.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=
=3D"A bar chart and a superimposed second chart. The two differ slightly, b=
ut both decrease in a similar fashion." src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org=
/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/Benfords_law_illustrated_by_world%27s_countri=
es_population.svg/250px-Benfords_law_illustrated_by_world%27s_countries_pop=
ulation.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"m=
w-file-element" data-file-width=3D"768" data-file-height=3D"576"></a><figca=
ption>Distribution of first digits (in&nbsp;%, red bars) in the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_countries_by_population" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"List of countries by population">population of the 237 c=
ountries</a> of the world. Black dots indicate the distribution predicted b=
y Benford's law.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Logarithms arise in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability=
_theory" title=3D"Probability theory">probability theory</a>: the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_large_numbers" title=3D"Law of lar=
ge numbers">law of large numbers</a> dictates that, for a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fair_coin" title=3D"Fair coin">fair coin</a>, as th=
e number of coin-tosses increases to infinity, the observed proportion of h=
eads <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution" title=
=3D"Binomial distribution">approaches one-half</a>. The fluctuations of thi=
s proportion about one-half are described by the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Law_of_the_iterated_logarithm" title=3D"Law of the iterated =
logarithm">law of the iterated logarithm</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-79" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note=
-79"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>74<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p><p>Logarithms also occur in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lo=
g-normal_distribution" title=3D"Log-normal distribution">log-normal distrib=
utions</a>. When the logarithm of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Random_variable" title=3D"Random variable">random variable</a> has a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal d=
istribution">normal distribution</a>, the variable is said to have a log-no=
rmal distribution.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-80" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-80"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Log-normal =
distributions are encountered in many fields, wherever a variable is formed=
 as the product of many independent positive random variables, for example =
in the study of turbulence.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-81" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-81"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Logarithms are used for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Max=
imum-likelihood_estimation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Maximum-likeliho=
od estimation">maximum-likelihood estimation</a> of parametric <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_model" title=3D"Statistical model"=
>statistical models</a>. For such a model, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Likelihood_function" title=3D"Likelihood function">likelihood =
function</a> depends on at least one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Parametric_model" title=3D"Parametric model">parameter</a> that must be =
estimated. A maximum of the likelihood function occurs at the same paramete=
r-value as a maximum of the logarithm of the likelihood (the "<i>log&nbsp;l=
ikelihood</i>"), because the logarithm is an increasing function. The log-l=
ikelihood is easier to maximize, especially for the multiplied likelihoods =
for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independence_(probability)" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Independence (probability)">independent</a> ra=
ndom variables.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-82" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-82"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benford%27s_law" title=3D"B=
enford's law">Benford's law</a> describes the occurrence of digits in many =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_set" title=3D"Data set">data =
sets</a>, such as heights of buildings. According to Benford's law, the pro=
bability that the first decimal-digit of an item in the data sample is <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> (from 1 to 9=
) equals <span class=3D"texhtml">log<sub>10</sub>=E2=80=89(<i>d</i> + 1) =
=E2=88=92 log<sub>10</sub>=E2=80=89(<i>d</i>)</span>, <i>regardless</i> of =
the unit of measurement.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-83" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-83"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Thus,=
 about 30% of the data can be expected to have 1 as first digit, 18% start =
with 2, etc. Auditors examine deviations from Benford's law to detect fraud=
ulent accounting.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-84" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-84"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>79<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm_transformatio=
n" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Logarithm transformation">logarithm trans=
formation</a> is a type of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_tr=
ansformation_(statistics)" title=3D"Data transformation (statistics)">data =
transformation</a> used to bring the empirical distribution closer to the a=
ssumed one.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computational_complexity">C=
omputational complexity</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Computational complexity"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis_of_algorithms" title=
=3D"Analysis of algorithms">Analysis of algorithms</a> is a branch of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D"Computer sci=
ence">computer science</a> that studies the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Time_complexity" title=3D"Time complexity">performance</a> of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algori=
thms</a> (computer programs solving a certain problem).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Wegener_85-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Logarithm#cite_note-Wegener-85"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>80<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Logarithms are valuable for des=
cribing algorithms that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divide_and=
_conquer_algorithm" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Divide and conquer algor=
ithm">divide a problem</a> into smaller ones, and join the solutions of the=
 subproblems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-86" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-86"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For example, to find a number in a sorted list, the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_search_algorithm" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Binary search algorithm">binary search algorithm</a> checks the middl=
e entry and proceeds with the half before or after the middle entry if the =
number is still not found. This algorithm requires, on average, <span class=
=3D"texhtml">log<sub>2</sub>=E2=80=89(<i>N</i>)</span> comparisons, where <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span> is the li=
st's length.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-87" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-87"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Similarly, the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merge_sort" title=3D"Merge sort">mer=
ge sort</a> algorithm sorts an unsorted list by dividing the list into halv=
es and sorting these first before merging the results. Merge sort algorithm=
s typically require a time <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_n=
otation" title=3D"Big O notation">approximately proportional to</a> <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>N</i> =C2=B7 log(<i>N</i>)</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8=
8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#c=
ite_note-88"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>83<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> The base of the logarithm is not specified here, b=
ecause the result only changes by a constant factor when another base is us=
ed. A constant factor is usually disregarded in the analysis of algorithms =
under the standard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_cost_mo=
del" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Uniform cost model">uniform cost model<=
/a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wegener20_89-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-Wegener20-89"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>84<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A function&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> is=
 said to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithmic_growth" title=
=3D"Logarithmic growth">grow logarithmically</a> if <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> is (exactly or approximately) proportional to th=
e logarithm of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x<=
/span>. (Biological descriptions of organism growth, however, use this term=
 for an exponential function.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-90" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-90"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>85<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
) For example, any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_number"=
 title=3D"Natural number">natural number</a>&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span> can be represented in <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_numeral_system" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Binary numeral system">binary form</a> in no more than <span class=
=3D"texhtml">log<sub>2</sub>=E2=80=89<i>N</i> + 1</span>&nbsp;<a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bit" title=3D"Bit">bits</a>. In other words, th=
e amount of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Memory_(computing)" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Memory (computing)">memory</a> needed to store=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span> grows l=
ogarithmically with <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">N</span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Entropy_and_chaos">Entropy =
and chaos</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLo=
garithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit section: Entropy =
and chaos"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Chaotic_Bunimovich_stadium.sv=
g" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"An oval shape with the traject=
ories of two particles." src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/f/fb/Chaotic_Bunimovich_stadium.svg/250px-Chaotic_Bunimovich_stad=
ium.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"125" class=3D"mw-fi=
le-element" data-file-width=3D"758" data-file-height=3D"379"></a><figcaptio=
n><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamical_billiards" title=3D"Dy=
namical billiards">Billiards</a> on an oval <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Billiard_table" title=3D"Billiard table">billiard table</a>. Two =
particles, starting at the center with an angle differing by one degree, ta=
ke paths that diverge chaotically because of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Reflection_(physics)" title=3D"Reflection (physics)">reflections=
</a> at the boundary.</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entropy" title=3D"Entropy">Entr=
opy</a> is broadly a measure of the disorder of some system. In <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_thermodynamics" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Statistical thermodynamics">statistical thermodynamics</a>, t=
he entropy&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">S=
</span> of some physical system is defined as
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle S=3D-k\sum _{i}p_{i}\ln(p_{i}).\,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>S</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>k</mi>
        <munder>
          <mo>=E2=88=91<!-- =E2=88=91 --></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>i</mi>
          </mrow>
        </munder>
        <msub>
          <mi>p</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>i</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mi>ln</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>p</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>i</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>.</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle S=3D-k\sum _{=
i}p_{i}\ln(p_{i}).\,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/4be67693caef12b846ed9cd173a0e7a340364d27" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -3.005ex; width:20.854ex; height:5.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle S=
=3D-k\sum _{i}p_{i}\ln(p_{i}).\,}"></span>
</p><p>The sum is over all possible states&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">i</span> of the system in question, such as =
the positions of gas particles in a container. Moreover, <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>p</i><sub><i>i</i></sub></span> is the probability that the state&=
nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">i</span> is =
attained and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</s=
pan> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boltzmann_constant" ti=
tle=3D"Boltzmann constant">Boltzmann constant</a>. Similarly, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entropy_(information_theory)" title=3D"Entropy =
(information theory)">entropy in information theory</a> measures the quanti=
ty of information. If a message recipient may expect any one of <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span> possible messages w=
ith equal likelihood, then the amount of information conveyed by any one su=
ch message is quantified as <span class=3D"texhtml">log<sub>2</sub>=E2=80=
=89<i>N</i></span> bits.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-91" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-91"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>86<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lyapunov_exponent" title=3D=
"Lyapunov exponent">Lyapunov exponents</a> use logarithms to gauge the degr=
ee of chaoticity of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamical_sy=
stem" title=3D"Dynamical system">dynamical system</a>. For example, for a p=
article moving on an oval billiard table, even small changes of the initial=
 conditions result in very different paths of the particle. Such systems ar=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chaos_theory" title=3D"Chaos the=
ory">chaotic</a> in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deterministi=
c_system" title=3D"Deterministic system">deterministic</a> way, because sma=
ll measurement errors of the initial state predictably lead to largely diff=
erent final states.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-92" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-92"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>87<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> At least o=
ne Lyapunov exponent of a deterministically chaotic system is positive.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fractals">Fractals</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" title=3D"Edit section: Fractals"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Sierpinski_dimension.svg" class=3D"mw-file-de=
scription"><img alt=3D"Parts of a triangle are removed in an iterated way."=
 src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Sierpinsk=
i_dimension.svg/250px-Sierpinski_dimension.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" widt=
h=3D"250" height=3D"36" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"745" d=
ata-file-height=3D"108"></a><figcaption>The Sierpinski triangle (at the rig=
ht) is constructed by repeatedly replacing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Equilateral_triangle" title=3D"Equilateral triangle">equilateral t=
riangles</a> by three smaller ones.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Logarithms occur in definitions of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Fractal_dimension" title=3D"Fractal dimension">dimension</a> of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractal" title=3D"Fractal">fractals</=
a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-93" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8=
8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Fractals are geometric obj=
ects that are self-similar in the sense that small parts reproduce, at leas=
t roughly, the entire global structure. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Sierpinski_triangle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sierpinski tr=
iangle">Sierpinski triangle</a> (pictured) can be covered by three copies o=
f itself, each having sides half the original length. This makes the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hausdorff_dimension" title=3D"Hausdorff =
dimension">Hausdorff dimension</a> of this structure <span class=3D"texhtml=
">ln(3)/ln(2) =E2=89=88 1.58</span>. Another logarithm-based notion of dime=
nsion is obtained by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box-counting_=
dimension" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Box-counting dimension">counting =
the number of boxes</a> needed to cover the fractal in question.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Music">Music</h3><span clas=
