</span></div></div></div><div class=3D"trow" style=3D"display:flex"><div cl=
ass=3D"thumbcaption">Four different octaves shown on a linear scale, then s=
hown on a logarithmic scale (as the ear hears them)</div></div></div></div>
<p>Logarithms are related to musical tones and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Interval_(music)" title=3D"Interval (music)">intervals</a>. In=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equal_temperament" title=3D"Equal=
 temperament">equal temperament</a> tunings, the frequency ratio depends on=
ly on the interval between two tones, not on the specific frequency, or <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pitch_(music)" title=3D"Pitch (music)=
">pitch</a>, of the individual tones. In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/12-tone_equal_temperament" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"12-ton=
e equal temperament">12-tone equal temperament</a> tuning common in modern =
Western music, each <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octave" title=
=3D"Octave">octave</a> (doubling of frequency) is broken into twelve equall=
y spaced intervals called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semitone=
" title=3D"Semitone">semitones</a>. For example, if the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_(musical_note)" title=3D"A (musical note)">note&nbs=
p;<i>A</i></a> has a frequency of 440&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Hertz" title=3D"Hertz">Hz</a> then the note <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/B%E2%99%AD_(musical_note)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"B=E2=99=AD (musical note)"><i>B-flat</i></a> has a frequency of 466&nbs=
p;Hz. The interval between <i>A</i> and <i>B-flat</i> is a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semitone" title=3D"Semitone">semitone</a>, as is t=
he one between <i>B-flat</i> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
_(musical_note)" title=3D"B (musical note)"><i>B</i></a> (frequency 493&nbs=
p;Hz). Accordingly, the frequency ratios agree:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle {\frac {466}{440}}\approx {\frac {493}{466}}\approx 1.0=
59\approx {\sqrt[{12}]{2}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mn>466</mn>
            <mn>440</mn>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=E2=89=88<!-- =E2=89=88 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mn>493</mn>
            <mn>466</mn>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=E2=89=88<!-- =E2=89=88 --></mo>
        <mn>1.059</mn>
        <mo>=E2=89=88<!-- =E2=89=88 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mroot>
            <mn>2</mn>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mn>12</mn>
            </mrow>
          </mroot>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\frac {466}{=
440}}\approx {\frac {493}{466}}\approx 1.059\approx {\sqrt[{12}]{2}}.}</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
