<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Inverses_of_other_exponenti=
al_functions">Inverses of other exponential functions</h3><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogarithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;s=
ection=3D37" title=3D"Edit section: Inverses of other exponential functions=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>Exponentiation occurs in many areas of mathematics and its inverse funct=
ion is often referred to as the logarithm. For example, the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm_of_a_matrix" title=3D"Logarithm of a ma=
trix">logarithm of a matrix</a> is the (multi-valued) inverse function of t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_exponential" title=3D"Ma=
trix exponential">matrix exponential</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-103" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-103=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>97<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> Another example is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/P-adic_logarithm_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"P-adic logarit=
hm function"><i>p</i>-adic logarithm</a>, the inverse function of the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-adic_exponential_function" title=3D"P=
-adic exponential function"><i>p</i>-adic exponential</a>. Both are defined=
 via Taylor series analogous to the real case.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-104" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_not=
e-104"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>98<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> In the context of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Differential_geometry" title=3D"Differential geometry">differential geom=
etry</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_map_(Rie=
mannian_geometry)" title=3D"Exponential map (Riemannian geometry)">exponent=
ial map</a> maps the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangent_space=
" title=3D"Tangent space">tangent space</a> at a point of a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differentiable_manifold" title=3D"Differentiable =
manifold">manifold</a> to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neighb=
orhood_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Neighborhood (mathemat=
ics)">neighborhood</a> of that point. Its inverse is also called the logari=
thmic (or log) map.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-105" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-105"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>99<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the context of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_gr=
oup" title=3D"Finite group">finite groups</a> exponentiation is given by re=
peatedly multiplying one group element&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> with itself. The <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_logarithm" title=3D"Discrete logarithm">discret=
e logarithm</a> is the integer&nbsp;<i><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span></i> solving the equation
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle b^{n}=3Dx,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mi>b</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>n</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle b^{n}=3Dx,}</=
annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/f90e5e0851759d0490e085cf1888338465384143" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.671ex; width:7.291ex; height:2.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle b^=
{n}=3Dx,}"></span>
</p><p>where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</s=
pan> is an element of the group. Carrying out the exponentiation can be don=
e efficiently, but the discrete logarithm is believed to be very hard to ca=
lculate in some groups. This asymmetry has important applications in <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_key_cryptography" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Public key cryptography">public key cryptography</a>, such =
as for example in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80=
%93Hellman_key_exchange" title=3D"Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman key exchange">Diff=
ie=E2=80=93Hellman key exchange</a>, a routine that allows secure exchanges=
 of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptography" title=3D"Cryptog=
raphy">cryptographic</a> keys over unsecured information channels.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-106" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Logarithm#cite_note-106"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>100<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Zech%27s_logarithm" title=3D"Zech's logarithm">Zech's logarithm</a>=
 is related to the discrete logarithm in the multiplicative group of non-ze=
ro elements of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_field" tit=
le=3D"Finite field">finite field</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-107" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-107"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>101<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"double_logarithm"></span>Further logari=
thm-like inverse functions include the <i>double logarithm</i>&nbsp;<span c=
lass=3D"texhtml">ln(ln(<i>x</i>))</span>, the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Super-logarithm" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Super-logari=
thm">super- or hyper-4-logarithm</a></i> (a slight variation of which is ca=
lled <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iterated_logarithm" title=3D"=
Iterated logarithm">iterated logarithm</a> in computer science), the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lambert_W_function" title=3D"Lambert W f=
unction">Lambert W function</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Logit" title=3D"Logit">logit</a>. They are the inverse functions of =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double_exponential_function" t=
itle=3D"Double exponential function">double exponential function</a>, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetration" title=3D"Tetration">tetratio=
n</a>, of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>w</i>) =3D <i>we<sup>w</sup><=
/i></span>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-108" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-108"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>102<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and of the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_function" title=3D"Logistic f=
unction">logistic function</a>, respectively.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-109" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note=
-109"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>103<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Related_concepts">Related c=
oncepts</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLoga=
rithm&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D38" title=3D"Edit section: Related co=
ncepts"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<p>From the perspective of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_t=
heory" title=3D"Group theory">group theory</a>, the identity <span class=3D=
"texhtml">log(<i>cd</i>) =3D log(<i>c</i>) + log(<i>d</i>)</span> expresses=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_isomorphism" title=3D"Gro=
up isomorphism">group isomorphism</a> between positive <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">reals</a> under mul=
tiplication and reals under addition. Logarithmic functions are the only co=
ntinuous isomorphisms between these groups.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-110" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note=
-110"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>104<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> By means of that isomorphism, the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Haar_measure" title=3D"Haar measure">Haar measure</a> (<=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebesgue_measure" title=3D"Lebesgue=
 measure">Lebesgue measure</a>)&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>dx</i></spa=
n> on the reals corresponds to the Haar measure&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>dx</i>/<i>x</i></span> on the positive reals.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-111" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm#cite=
_note-111"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>105<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> The non-negative reals not only have a multiplicati=
on, but also have addition, and form a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Semiring" title=3D"Semiring">semiring</a>, called the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_semiring" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Probability semiring">probability semiring</a>; this is in fact a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semifield" title=3D"Semifield">semifiel=
d</a>. The logarithm then takes multiplication to addition (log multiplicat=
ion), and takes addition to log addition (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/LogSumExp" title=3D"LogSumExp">LogSumExp</a>), giving an <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isomorphism" title=3D"Isomorphism">isomorphi=
sm</a> of semirings between the probability semiring and the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Log_semiring" title=3D"Log semiring">log semirin=
g</a>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithmic_form" title=3D"=
Logarithmic form">Logarithmic one-forms&nbsp;</a><span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>df</i>/<i>f</i></span> appear in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Complex_analysis" title=3D"Complex analysis">complex analysis</a> and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_geometry" title=3D"Algebraic =
geometry">algebraic geometry</a> as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Differential_form" title=3D"Differential form">differential forms</a> wit=
h logarithmic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pole_(complex_analys=
is)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pole (complex analysis)">poles</a>.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-112" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Logarithm#cite_note-112"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>106<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polylogarithm" title=3D=
"Polylogarithm">polylogarithm</a> is the function defined by
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
